{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e34829a8-1b91-4abe-bac5-0789f1d29317","content":"The standard approach is to **wrap them behind an interface** and inject it:\n\n```csharp\npublic interface IFileSystem\n{\n    string ReadAllText(string path);\n    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);\n    bool DirectoryExists(string path);\n}\n```\n\nThen a real implementation for production:\n\n```csharp\npublic class FileSystem : IFileSystem\n{\n    public string ReadAllText(string path) => File.ReadAllText(path);\n    public void WriteAllText(string path, string contents) => File.WriteAllText(path, contents);\n    public bool DirectoryExists(string path) => Directory.Exists(path);\n}\n```\n\n**In your classes**, inject `IFileSystem` instead of calling `File`/`Directory` directly. **In tests**, pass a mock or in-memory fake.\n\nAlternatively, the **[System.IO.Abstractions](https://www.nuget.org/packages/System.IO.Abstractions)** NuGet package provides a ready-made `IFileSystem` with a `MockFileSystem` for testing — saves you from hand-rolling the interface:\n\n```\ndotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions\ndotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"17cae77f-d4fe-44f2-9d1c-8532bbfc5a49","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to make file system operations testable in their .NET/C# project. They have `File.WriteAllText`, `File.ReadAllText`, and `Directory.Exists` calls scattered across their code.\n\nThis is a general software engineering question, not a codebase-specific task. I should give a concise answer about the standard approach.\n\nThe standard approach is to introduce a file system abstraction (interface) and use dependency injection. Let me give a concise answer.","outputTokens":424,"requestId":"CFC7:32055B:DF3C337:F8EF946:69EC1D36"},"id":"aa79fd65-c77a-449e-9ac2-0379b2d732b8","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:47:44.462Z","parentId":"11e6ef0a-8fb7-4e69-bb27-8db18c21e261"}
